# Refactored with Async/Await

```javascript
async function getUser(id) {
  const rows = await db.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?', [id]);

  if (!rows.length) {
    throw new Error('Not found');
  }

  return rows[0];
}
```

## Usage Comparison

**Original (Callback):**
```javascript
getUser(123, (err, user) => {
  if (err) {
    console.error(err);
  } else {
    console.log(user);
  }
});
```

**Refactored (Async/Await):**
```javascript
try {
  const user = await getUser(123);
  console.log(user);
} catch (err) {
  console.error(err);
}
```

## Key Changes

| Aspect | Callback | Async/Await |
|--------|----------|------------|
| **Error handling** | Callback parameter | `throw`/`try-catch` |
| **Return value** | Via callback | Direct `return` |
| **Readability** | Nested callbacks | Linear code flow |
| **Syntax** | Error-first pattern | Standard exceptions |

## Note
This assumes your `db.query()` method already returns a Promise. If it doesn't, you'll need to promisify it first:

```javascript
const db = require('your-db-library').promises;
// or
const util = require('util');
db.query = util.promisify(db.query);
```

